{
  "answer": "**The work is the *Parāśara Smṛti* (*unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be*), Chapter 7.**[^1]\n\nThe age-by-age naming of the girl—from *Gaurī* in her eighth year, *Rohiṇī* in her ninth, and *Kanyā* in her tenth, after which she becomes a *rajasvalā*—is given in verses Par_7.4–5:\n\n> [p-dda364] one becomes pure by drawing out one hundred pots of water and using *pañcagavya*. An eight-year-old girl is a Gaurī; a nine-year-old is a Rohiṇī. (II,1, p. 156) // Par_7.4 //<br>\n> [p-4665dc] A ten-year-old girl is a Kanyā; after that, she is a *rajasvalā* (a menstruating woman). He who does not give his daughter in marriage when she has reached her twelfth year, (II,1, p. 157) // Par_7.5 //[^2]\n\nThe twelfth-year sanction follows immediately in Par_7.6:\n\n> [p-513c49] her ancestors themselves drink her menstrual blood month after month. The mother, and the father, and likewise the eldest brother, (II,1, p. 158) // Par_7.6 //[^3]\n\n[^1]: *Parāśara Smṛti*, [Chapter 7](/works/unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be/07/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Parāśara Smṛti*, [Chapter 7](/works/unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be/07/translation/#p-dda364).\n\n[^3]: *Parāśara Smṛti*, [Chapter 7](/works/unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be/07/translation/#p-513c49).",
